Mozart or Salieri?¶

Classifying sound files using a Support Vector Machine to recognize one of two composers.

Making a dataset¶

mozart and salieri piano concertos

In [ ]:
!sudo curl -L https://yt-dl.org/downloads/latest/youtube-dl -o /usr/local/bin/youtube-dl
!sudo chmod a+rx /usr/local/bin/youtube-dl
import os
def youtube_downloader(urls, prefix, format='mp3', ytdl="/usr/local/bin/youtube-dl"):
    """Run the youtube downloader on all urls
    
    usage
    ------------
    >>> youtube_urls = [
    >>> "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DAf5sQ1ZsCY",
    >>> "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JamPSbdhLko",
    >>> "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MS3X0vy23dA",
    >>> "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2cPibJzwbA",
    >>> ]
    >>> filenames = youtube_downloader(youtube_urls, prefix="bach_chorale-1")
    Downloading...
    https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DAf5sQ1ZsCY bach_chorale-1-0.mp3
    https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JamPSbdhLko bach_chorale-1-1.mp3
    https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MS3X0vy23dA bach_chorale-1-2.mp3
    https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2cPibJzwbA bach_chorale-1-3.mp3
    Done.
    """
    
    if isinstance(urls,str):
        urls = [urls]
    print("Downloading...")
    filenames = []
    for i, url in enumerate(urls):
        out = f"{prefix}-{i}.{format}"
        print(url,out)
        flags = f" --output '{out}' "
        flags += f" --ignore-errors --extract-audio "
        flags += f" --audio-format {format} "
        os.system(f"{ytdl} {flags} {url}")
        filenames.append(out)
    print("Done.")
    return filenames

Make the Features¶

analyze your dataset into a feature dataset

In [ ]:
import sklearn
import numpy as np
In [ ]:
# define our scaler class
scaler = sklearn.preprocessing.StandardScaler()

# define a helper routine to compute the features on an audio file
def compute_features(audio):
    mfcc = librosa.feature.mfcc(audio, sr=sr, n_mfcc=11).T
    return scaler.fit_transform(mfcc)
In [ ]:
mozart_train_feats = compute_features(mozart_train)
salieri_train_feats = compute_features(salieri_train)
# stack features up, mozart first, salieri second
features = np.vstack((mozart_train_feats,salieri_train_feats))

Make the Labels¶

In [ ]:
# label 0 is mozart, label 1 is salieri (mozart first, salieri second)
labels = np.concatenate((
    np.zeros(len(mozart_train_feats)), # an array of ZEROS for mozart
    np.ones(len(salieri_train_feats))  # an array of ONES for salieri
    ))

Using our model¶

making predictions

In [ ]:
def prediction(model, composer, duration=(10,2), offset=(60,30) ):
    # randomly choose an offset and duration to load the file
    # these are ranges taen from duration and offset argument 
    # which are in tuples in seconds denoting: (range, offset)
    offset   = np.random.randint(offset[0])   + offset[1] 
    duration = np.random.randint(duration[0]) + duration[1]
    # load the test audio
    y_test, _ = librosa.load(composer, offset=offset, duration=duration, sr=sr)
    # compute test features
    test_features = compute_features(y_test)
    # run prediction on test features
    p = model.predict(test_features)

    # trick to get only one prediction
    p_u, p_c = np.unique(p,return_counts=True)
    pred = p_u[(np.argmax(p_c))]
    
    if pred == 0.0:
        print(composer, pred, "Mozart")
    else:
        print(composer, pred, "Salieri")
   

    ipd.display(ipd.Audio(y_test, rate=sr))

Grid Search for best parameters¶

Finally, we can use a grid search cross-validation to explore combinations of parameters. Here we will adjust C (which controls the margin hardness) and gamma (which controls the size of the radial basis function kernel), and determine the best model:

In [ ]:
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
In [ ]:
# param_grid = { 'C': [10, 50, 25], 'gamma': [0.01, 0.001, 0.0055] }
param_grid = { 'C': [50, 75], 'gamma': [0.01, 0.05] }
In [ ]:
# Feed in the best cross-validated model 'm' and the parameter grid
grid = GridSearchCV(m, param_grid, verbose=3)
In [ ]:
%time grid.fit(X_train, y_train)
print(grid.best_params_)

Classification Report¶

In [ ]:
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report
In [ ]:
# run prediction on all TEST features
yfit = best_model.predict(X_test)

# TEST labels as names
names = np.where(y_test==1,'Salieri','Mozart') 

# compute report on TEST prediction, passing the TEST (true) labels
report = classification_report(
                                y_test,            # true labels
                                yfit,              # predicted labels
                                labels=labels,     # all labels
                                target_names=names # test labels as names
                               )
print(report)
